"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424001","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>Current legislation requires the eyesight element of the practical driving test to be conducted in good daylight and prohibits learner drivers from motorways. The learning to drive and testing processes are, however, kept under review. The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) is currently trialling a series of potential changes aimed at encouraging learner drivers to obtain a wider range of driving experience prior to the practical driving test. This will include driving on roads which require a higher speed and other varying traffic situations. DVSA is also developing clips that depict hazards related to driving at night for inclusion in the hazard perception element of the theory test<strong>.</strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-30T12:32:12.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424001/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424001/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will give consideration to introducing the testing of (a) night-time and (b) motorway driving as mandatory components of the driving test.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","13459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424002","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-02","<p>The UK remains a strong and active supporter of the Global Fund and has pledged a contribution of up to £1 billion between 2014 and 2016 for the Global Fund’s 4th replenishment, subject to a 10% donor share cap. As part of this, in 2015-16 the UK has contributed £100m.</p><br /><p>The 5th replenishment, for 2017-2019, has not been launched yet, so the UK contribution has not yet been determined.</p><br /><p>The UK has contributed £2.05bn to the Global Fund since its inception. From a standing start in 2002, the UK’s unwavering support has enabled the Global Fund to keep 8.1 million people alive with HIV therapy, distribute 548 million mosquito nets, detect and treat 13.2 million cases on TB, and has contributed to a decline of one third in the number of people dying from the three diseases since 2002 in Global Fund countries.</p><br /><p>The UK has contributed: £128m in 2011/12; £128m in 2012/13; £543m in 2013/14; £285m in 2014/15, and; £100m 2015/16. This totals £1.184bn over the 5-year period.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","13370","2015-11-02T16:55:35.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424002/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424002/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-26","Global Fund to Fight Aids, Tuberculosis and Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding her Department has contributed to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB and Malaria (a) since the creation of that fund and (b) in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","13371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424003","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-02","<p>Through the UK Government’s International Climate Fund DFID has worked with the World Health Organisation to assess the effect that climate change will have on water and sanitation facilities and has produced a joint report titled ‘Vision 2030’. This outlines the evidence, and sets out what can be done to optimise the resilience of water and sanitation technologies, infrastructure and services. DFID has also funded the Overseas Development Institute to produce a report assessing the risks that climate change poses to the delivery of Water Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) programmes. All of DFID’s WASH programmes require sustainability and climate risks to be taken into account in design and delivery.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-11-02T16:56:46.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424003/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424003/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-26","Developing Countries: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect that climate change is having on (a) clean water and (b) adequate sanitation facilities in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","13369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424004","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-02","<p>The UK remains a strong and active supporter of the Global Fund and has pledged a contribution of up to £1 billion between 2014 and 2016 for the Global Fund’s 4th replenishment, subject to a 10% donor share cap. As part of this, in 2015-16 the UK has contributed £100m.</p><br /><p>The 5th replenishment, for 2017-2019, has not been launched yet, so the UK contribution has not yet been determined.</p><br /><p>The UK has contributed £2.05bn to the Global Fund since its inception. From a standing start in 2002, the UK’s unwavering support has enabled the Global Fund to keep 8.1 million people alive with HIV therapy, distribute 548 million mosquito nets, detect and treat 13.2 million cases on TB, and has contributed to a decline of one third in the number of people dying from the three diseases since 2002 in Global Fund countries.</p><br /><p>The UK has contributed: £128m in 2011/12; £128m in 2012/13; £543m in 2013/14; £285m in 2014/15, and; £100m 2015/16. This totals £1.184bn over the 5-year period.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","13371","2015-11-02T16:55:34.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424004/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424004/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-26","Global Fund to Fight Aids, Tuberculosis and Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department plans to contribute to the Global Fund in financial years (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","13370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424005","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>Although we are now recording management information on the number of women who have disclosed their pregnancy to the Home Office, collection of data about the detention of pregnant women will be limited.</p><p>We will not necessarily be aware that a woman is pregnant unless she chooses to make this known to us and a woman may not know herself that she is pregnant when she enters detention. It may not always be appropriate for healthcare professionals to disclose information that the patient has asked not to be disclosed.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-04T17:25:31.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424005/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424005/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-26","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Pregnancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many pregnant women are detained at Yarl's Wood.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","13393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424006","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>We take our arms export responsibilities very seriously and the UK operates one of the most rigorous and transparent arms export control regimes in the world. All defence and dual-use exports are required to meet the UK’s strict export control requirements, which include consideration of the UK’s international commitments including under international treaties and obligations. We do not issue an export licence if there is a clear risk that the proposed export might be used in the commission of a serious violation of international humanitarian law. We also take account of any risk that the goods might be diverted to undesirable end-users or end-use.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-03T14:30:30.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424006/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424006/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-26","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will suspend the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","13490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424007","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>The Convention on Cluster Munitions obliges States Parties to promote adherence to the Convention, and to encourage non-States Parties to accede to it. The UK, in line with these Convention commitments, encourages all states not party to accede to the Convention as soon as possible to further prevent the use, development, production, acquisition, stockpiling, retention and transfer of cluster munitions. The UK continues to encourage Saudi Arabia to accede to the Convention both bilaterally and in multinational fora.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-03T14:25:33.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424007/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424007/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-26","Saudi Arabia: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to encourage Saudi Arabia to destroy its stock of cluster munitions.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","13390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424008","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>We take seriously the reports of alleged violations of international humanitarian law (IHL) and abuses of human rights in Yemen, by all sides to the conflict. We have raised our concerns with Saudi Arabia and other members of the Coalition, and have received repeated assurances of compliance with IHL. We continue to engage with them on those assurances. We are also concerned by reports of alleged IHL violations by Houthi-Saleh forces. We have raised our concerns with the Houthis on the importance of compliance with IHL.</p><p>The UK supported the resolution adopted at the recent session of the Human Rights Council which, inter alia, called upon all parties in Yemen to respect their obligations under international humanitarian law, and requested that the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights assist the Yemeni national independent commission of inquiry. This assistance should help the government of Yemen to meet its international obligations in investigating reports of violations of human rights law and international humanitarian law.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-03T15:05:59.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424008/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424008/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-26","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will discuss with his international counterpart the possibility of setting up a judicial mechanism to independently and impartially investigate reports of violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","13389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424009","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. These are available on the Parliament website: <a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html" target="_blank">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html</a></p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-28T17:20:21.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424009/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424009/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-26","Social Security Benefits: Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the provisions in Clauses 13 and 14 of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on the welfare of cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","13392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424010","Department of Health","false","2015-11-02","<p>The Department commissioned the Review of Choice in End of Life Care to examine the issue of choice in end of life care. The Review’s recommendations on achieving high quality care and greater choice were published earlier this year. We agree with the vision set out by the Review and we are working with NHS England to see how this can best be achieved. We intend to respond to the Review later this year.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-02T17:39:15.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424010/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424010/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-26","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress his Department has made on the implementation of the Choice Review.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","13391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424011","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-09","<p>Information on 19 to 24 years olds who completed a Level 3 qualification on the Regulated Qualifications Framework prior to starting a Level 2 Apprenticeship in 2013/14 is not available.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-09T10:08:17.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424011/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424011/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-26","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many 19 to 24 year olds who already had a Level 3 qualification on the regulated qualifications framework started a Level 2 apprenticeship framework in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","13494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424012","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Department appointed the consultant for the London and South Coast Rail Corridor Study in September. In October, the Government published the Study Terms of Reference on its website. Ministers anticipate receiving the findings by the end of 2015.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-29T12:42:53.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424012/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424012/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Railways: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to appoint the consultant for the London and South Coast rail corridor study.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","13495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424013","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Department anticipates receiving the findings of the London and South Coast Rail Corridor Study by the end of 2015. The Government will subsequently consider the timeframe for releasing the study findings, including our response.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-29T12:50:43.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424013/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424013/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Railways: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the London and South Coast rail corridor study to be published.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","13496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424014","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-29","<p>Local authorities have the power and responsibility to provide adequate parking provision in their area. They are best placed to understand and ensure the parking needs of their local communities are met. It would be inappropriate for Central Government to intervene in this matter. Communities now have the opportunity to challenge local authorities' parking policies if they think provision is inadequate. This is set out at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/right-to-challenge-parking-policies.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","13427","2015-10-29T16:00:02.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424014/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424014/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-26","Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what support his Department is providing to local authorities to meet localised demand for parking spaces; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424015","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-29","<p>Local authorities have the power and responsibility to provide adequate parking provision in their area. They are best placed to understand and ensure the parking needs of their local communities are met. It would be inappropriate for Central Government to intervene in this matter. Communities now have the opportunity to challenge local authorities' parking policies if they think provision is inadequate. This is set out at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/right-to-challenge-parking-policies.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","13430","2015-10-29T16:00:02.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424015/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424015/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-26","Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has carried out of the adequacy of parking capacity across local authorities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424016","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-30","<p>As set out in the November 2013 Renewable Energy Roadmap Update, analysis indicated a potential deployment range of 7-20 GW (equivalent to 6-18 TWh) of solar PV at all scales, with 20GW being our estimate of the technical maximum level of solar PV deployment by 2020 on the basis of grid and other constraints. Solar PV in the UK was 8.007GW as of August 2015<sup>1</sup>.</p><br /><p>In the absence of cost effective storage, solar PV can make a contribution to meeting electricity demand but this will be limited by the nature of its diurnal cycle.</p><br /><p><em>REF:</em></p><ol><li><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solar-pv-deployment-august-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solar-pv-deployment-august-2015</a></em></li></ol>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-30T13:35:30.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424016/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424016/answer","South Northamptonshire","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424016/answer/previousversion/26585","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424016/answer/previousversion/26585","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-26","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent assessment her Department has made of the ability of the UK solar industry to meet service demand; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424017","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-06","<p>Licensing and consent of onshore oil and gas activities in England is now a matter for the Oil and Gas Authority (OGA). Petroleum Exploration and Development Licences are not specific to shale gas. They grant exclusive rights to extract hydrocarbons, including shale gas but also other hydrocarbons, within a particular onshore area. A separate consent from the OGA is required before any drilling or hydraulic fracturing (fracking) can take place, as well as planning permission, environmental permits and review of the well design by the Health and Safety Executive.</p><br /><p>The OGA does not have any undetermined consent applications.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-06T13:46:24.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424017/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424017/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-26","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many sites are approved for fracking in England and Wales; what the location is of each such site; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424018","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-02","<p>The Written Ministerial Statement by my rt. hon. Friends, the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change and the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on 16 September 2015 (<em>Official Report, Column 34-38WS</em>), sets out the Government’s view that there is a national need to explore and develop our shale gas and oil resources in a safe, sustainable and timely way, to help meet our objectives for secure energy supplies, economic growth and lower carbon emissions.</p><br /><p>A successful shale industry could help create jobs and grow local economies. Investment in shale could reach £33billion and support up to 64,000 jobs in oil, gas, construction, engineering and chemical sectors. The opportunity to extract this energy, as well as to secure jobs and investment, cannot be ignored.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-02T15:40:29.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424018/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424018/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-26","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent assessment her Department has made of the role of fracking in meeting the future energy needs of the UK; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424019","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-02","<p>Meals offered to prisoners are nutritious, balanced, varied and in line with government recommendations on eating a healthy diet.</p><br /><p>Last year, National Offender Management Service developed a model of cyclical four week menus, working closely withtheir food suppliers and nutritional technologists. As part of this process, a dietary and nutritional specialist was commissioned to review, analyse and make recommendations on the overall balance and nutritional content of the menus. These recommendations were incorporated and the menus are available to Prison Catering Teams.</p><br /><p>Prisons are also encouraged to seek nutritional advice on any changes to menus to ensure they meet national standards.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-11-02T10:39:46.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424019/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424019/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-26","Prisoners: Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2015 to Question 12252, what plans his Department has to increase the nutritional content of meals served to the prison population.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424020","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-03","<p>The level of public subsidy paid to (or premiums paid by) train operators is determined by the franchising process, in which bidders compete for the right to run passenger services franchises. Franchise competitions are designed to allow train operators an adequate financial return while at the same time ensuring they can fulfil their franchise commitments and obligations in full. Last year the Department received net £1.2bn premium from franchised train operators. Further information can be found on the Gov.uk website</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rail-subsidy-per-passenger-mile" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rail-subsidy-per-passenger-mile</a>).</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-11-03T11:28:05.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424020/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424020/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Train Operating Companies: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2015 to Question 12620, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of the level of public subsidy for train operators in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424021","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<br /><p>The Road Investment Strategy (RIS) published in December 2014 sets out how £15.2 billion is being invested between 2015 and 2021 to improve the Strategic Road Network (SRN) - motorways and major ‘A’ roads in England. The RIS takes into account a range of possible outcomes for the future, underpinned by broad evidence which the Department will continue to build on and review. This includes an assessment of the trends that are likely to have a significant impact on road use and what these trends mean for traffic volumes on the SRN.</p><br /><p>On the local road network it is for local highway authorities to make assessments of need and consider improvements.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-29T16:41:20.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424021/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424021/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Roads","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has carried out of the ability of road infrastructure to meet future demand; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","13429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424022","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-29","<p>Raytheon acted as the Hackathon sponsor at the Chief Information Officer's Information Symposium in June. No other events have been sponsored by the company in the last 12 months.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-10-29T16:33:48.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424022/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424022/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-26","Ministry of Defence: Raytheon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which events held by his Department were sponsored by Raytheon in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","13456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424023","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-29","<p>I attended a dinner hosted by Raytheon on 21 January 2015. No further Ministers, Senior Military personnel or Ministry of Defence officials have received any other form of hospitality.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-10-29T16:40:22.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424023/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424023/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-26","Ministry of Defence: Raytheon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what hospitality was provided to (a) Ministers and officials of his Department and (b) members of the armed forces by Raytheon in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","13457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424024","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>The information is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-29T14:39:51.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424024/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424024/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-26","Working Age Benefits: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many former members of each branch of the armed forces are in receipt of (a) child and (b) working tax credits.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","13458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424025","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>The 23 March Board Investment and Commercial Committee ‎meeting was attended by senior officials from the Department for Transport. No Ministers or advisers were present.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-29T11:54:41.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424025/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424025/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Railways: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2015 to Question 12539, whether the meeting of the Board Investment and Commercial Committee on 23 March 2015 was attended by (a) Ministers in his Department, (b) special advisers in his Department and (c) officials in the Senior Civil Service grades.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424026","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Secretary of State announced on 25 June 2015 the pause of work on Midland Main Line electrification and TransPennine electrification. Network Rail subsequently announced to stakeholders that it was pausing work on Ely to Soham track doubling. No other pauses have been announced.</p><br /><p>Any further changes to Network Rail’s delivery plans will be announced as part of the outcome of Sir Peter Hendy’s review.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-29T14:56:03.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424026/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424026/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2015 to Question 12538, and with reference to the statement in the Answer of 21 September 2015 to Question 10029 that Ely to Soham track doubling was among a small number of schemes that had been paused by Network Rail, which other schemes were paused by Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424027","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>Further to my answers to earlier questions of 15 and 23 October (questions 11430 and 12213) on the subject of claims for Bus Service Operator Grant for school services, where we have identified claims in the past for closed school services these have been disallowed. However, as was made clear in the letter which my officials have sent recently to all operators, my Department will take the strongest possible measures against any operator who knowingly claims for such ineligible services in future.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-29T17:03:51.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424027/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424027/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Bus Service Operators Grant: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2015 to Question 12213, whether his Department has imposed any penalties on bus operators who submitted ineligible claims for Bus Service Operators Grant support for closed school bus services.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424028","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>In June 2015, as part of the affordability review exercise, Network Rail informed Department that the latest estimated cost of Great Western electrification was around £2.4bn. This forecast costs remained uncertain and further work was required to validate this figure. The validation is being undertaken as part of the Hendy review and we await the publication in the Autumn.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-29T14:09:19.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424028/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424028/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when Network Rail first informed his Department of their estimate that electrification of the Great Western Main Line would cost more than £2 billion.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424029","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<br /><p>Total expenditure on the Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) in each year from 2010-11 to 2014-15 in accrual terms and rounded to the nearest £million is set out below.</p><br /><p>2010-11 £445m</p><p>2011-12 £441m</p><p>2012-13 £344m</p><p>2013-14 £291m</p><p>2014/15 £253m</p><br /><p>Since 1 October 2013, the BSOG which was previously paid to bus operators for running bus services under franchise to Transport for London (TfL) in London has been incorporated into the general grant paid to TfL and the Greater London Authority. The figures given above exclude some £47 million paid to TfL/GLA in this way for 2013/14 and some £93 million paid to them for 2014/15.</p><br /><p>The figures given for 2013/14 onwards are made up of (i) BSOG paid to bus companies and community transport operators for running services outside London, (ii) BSOG devolved to local transport authorities in the five areas which have been designated as Better Bus Areas, and (iii) BSOG for tendered (non-commercially viable) services outside London for which the funding has been devolved to individual local authorities since 1 January 2014.</p><br /><p>As BSOG is a demand-led grant, it is too early to give an accurate projection of spend for 2015/16. However, we would expect it to be broadly similar to that for 2014-15.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-29T17:00:27.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424029/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424029/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's expenditure on the Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) was in each year from 2010-11 to 2014-15; and what his Department's projected expenditure on the BSOG is in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424030","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-02","<br /><p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the Rt. Hon. Member for Knowsley, George Howarth on 24 June 2015, PQs UIN 2944 and 2945.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","13316","2015-11-02T14:24:19.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424030/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424030/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-26","Slaughterhouses: CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to increase the use of CCTV in slaughterhouses; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","13486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424031","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-02","<p>All approved slaughterhouses are inspected every day they operate. Slaughterhouses are also audited a minimum of once every 12 months, with a greater frequency of audits where deficiencies have been identified during previous audits.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-11-02T09:46:07.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424031/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424031/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-26","Slaughterhouses: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of UK slaughterhouses were inspected in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","13317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424032","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-02","<br /><p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the Rt. Hon. Member for Knowsley, George Howarth on 24 June 2015, PQs UIN 2944 and 2945.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","13486","2015-11-02T14:24:19.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424032/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424032/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-26","Slaughterhouses: CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the opinion of the Farm Animal Welfare Committee on CCTV in slaughterhouses, published in February 2015.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","13316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424033","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-29","<p>China is a key partner for the Government to work with in combating the illegal trade in wildlife. In the <em>UK-China Joint Statement on Building a Global Comprehensive Strategic Partnership for the 21st Century</em>, issued on 22<sup>nd</sup> October on the occasion of the State Visit of President Xi Jinping, the UK and China recognised the importance and urgency of combating the illegal wildlife trade, and committed to take active measures to tackle this global challenge. We warmly welcome the recent announcement by China that it intends, in due course, to close its legal domestic market for ivory, and will continue to work with China to encourage this to happen as soon as feasible.</p><p>The Government is committed to maintaining the current global ban on any new international trade in ivory. In addition, the UK does not permit trade in raw ivory tusks of any age and we are pressing for this approach to be taken across the whole of the European Union.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-10-29T16:03:37.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424033/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424033/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-26","China: Ivory","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress the Government made during recent discussions with the Chinese Prime Minister in agreeing a timetable for closing legal ivory markets at international and domestic levels.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","13289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424034","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>An announcement regarding the toll levels for the Severn River Crossings is made by the concessionaire every year, and I understand they will announce in the coming weeks the 2016 toll levels. The Severn Bridges Act 1992 stipulates the level of increases in Severn tolls each year – in line with RPI during the concession period.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-29T11:30:41.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424034/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424034/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, at what level tolls at the Severn Bridge will be set from January 2016.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","13472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424035","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office Ministers and officials regularly encourage Turkey to continue to work towards the full protection of fundamental rights, including the principles of freedom of expression and freedom of the press. I discussed these issues, in the context of Turkey’s accession to the EU, when I last met my Turkish counterpart in August this year.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-29T15:36:56.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424035/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424035/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-26","Turkey: Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to his oral contribution of 20 October 2015, Official Report, column 813, what discussions he has had with ministers in the Turkish government on ensuring that freedom of the press is upheld in that country as it relates to citizens of any country.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","13331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424036","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-29","<p>Published figures can be found at the following link: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2015" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2015</a>.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-10-29T16:42:07.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424036/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424036/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-26","Entry Clearances: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the average time taken to secure appeal hearings for people whose entry clearance applications have been refused.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","13298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424037","Scotland Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>I have had a number of meetings and discussions on the important issue of opencast restoration over recent months, including with Local Authorities affected and colleagues from HM Treasury, the Department of Energy and Climate Change and the Scottish Government.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-10-29T16:30:11.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424037/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424037/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-10-26","Opencast Mining: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent representations he has received on measures to rehabilitate land which has been defaced by opencast mining; and what steps he plans to take in response to those representations.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","13439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424216","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>The government is devolving Air Passenger Duty to the Scottish Parliament through the Scotland Bill. Ministers are in ongoing discussions with the Scottish Government about all aspects of the Scotland Bill and the terms of the fiscal framework.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-29T17:27:51.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424216/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424216/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-26","Air Passenger Duty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with Ministers in the Scottish Government on the transfer of responsibility for Air Passenger Duty to the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","901868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424678","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>The only railway infrastructure in Britain that can accommodate a rail freight service carrying lorry trailers is HS1 between the Channel Tunnel and Barking, which can carry the standard international 4 metres semi-trailer. It represents 0.75% per cent of Britain’s rail route mileage.</p><br /><p>The 80% of the UK domestic semi-trailer fleet with a height of 4.25 metres or greater cannot be accommodated on trains in Britain. However, container goods can be accepted across the freight network, which carries some 1 million containers – 30% of total container freight in the UK - a year.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-29T14:51:32.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424678/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424678/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of the railway is able to accommodate the transport of full-sized lorry trailers on trains.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","901885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424757","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>Highways England combine maintenance and improvement schemes to maximise activity within roadworks. However, lane closures are sometimes left in place through the day and then work undertaken overnight. Removing these completely each day would be time consuming and would delay projects and motorists for longer.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-29T13:36:16.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424757/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424757/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Motorways: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to minimise the extent and length of road works on the motorway network at times when work is not taking place.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","901880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424758","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>I was delighted that the Infrastructure Act included a firm commitment to deliver a Cycling &amp; Walking Investment Strategy (CWIS). We will be ready to commence a formal consultation on this in Spring 2016.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-29T13:44:27.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424758/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424758/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Cycling and Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department has made on publishing a cycling and walking investment strategy.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","901882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424759","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-29","<p>We have made significant progress on increasing access. By the end of the year, we expect around 75% of rail journeys to start or end at a step-free station. That is an increase from around 50% when the Access for All programme started. That programme will deliver 151 step-free routes at stations this year. On the buses, only 57% met accessibility regulations in 2009-10. That number is now nearly 90% and rising.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-29T13:55:50.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424759/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424759/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-26","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's policies on increasing access to public transport for disabled passengers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","901881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423482","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-04","We are aware of reports of attacks by Hindu extremists on minority groups in India. The UK raises human rights matters with India, including attacks on minority groups, both bilaterally and through the EU-India human rights dialogue. As part of an EU delegation, our High Commission in New Delhi met the Indian National Commission for Minorities in early October to discuss a range of current issues. Our High Commission also maintains regular contact with civil society organisations and senior faith leaders working on religious freedom across India.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-04T14:00:44.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423482/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423482/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-23","India: Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of India about the number of attacks on minorities by extremist groups in that country, in particular black ink attacks carried out by Shiv Sena.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423483","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-06","The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs , my right hon. Friend the Member for East Devon (Mr Swire), has previously raised this case with Prime Minister Modi in his former role as Chief Minister of Gujarat. We continue to raise consular matters with the Indian authorities at all levels. Our officials have provided consular support to the families since 2002 and will continue to provide assistance to them as needed.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-06T12:08:46.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423483/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423483/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-23","India: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to raise with Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi the case of three British citizens murdered in Gujarat in 2002 when he visits the United Kingdom in November.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423484","Home Office","false","2015-11-06","<p>The Home Office do not routinely comment on individual cases. The Home Office has obligations in law to protect this information.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-06T13:27:41.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423484/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423484/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Narendra Modi","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether restrictions were imposed on the travel of Narendra Modi; if so, whether such restrictions have been lifted; and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423485","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-02","As the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr. Hammond) said on 9 October, “We condemn all acts of violence, including attacks by Palestinians and by Israeli settlers. We urge all sides to take immediate steps to de-escalate the tensions and avoid actions that threaten to exacerbate the situation”. In his Statement of 13 October, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr. Ellwood), said, “We are also concerned by the use of force by Israeli security personnel in response to protests and security incidents”.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-02T14:30:36.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423485/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423485/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-23","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports regarding increasing violence towards Palestinians by Israeli troops.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423486","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>The UK has made clear in conversations with the Palestinian Authority and the Israeli government that the best way to achieve a just and lasting resolution that ends the occupation and delivers peace for both Israelis and Palestinians is through negotiations. However, in order to achieve this, there must be an environment conductive to peace. That is why since the start of the current violence we have spoken regularly to both the Palestinian Authority and the Israeli government, urging them to use their influence to de-escalate the tensions.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-02T14:31:18.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423486/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423486/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-23","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have provided any advice to (1) the Palestinian authorities, and (2) the government of Israel, regarding the peace plan or the two-state solution.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423487","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>The assessment of the structure, roles and purpose of paramilitary organisations in Northern Ireland, published on 20 October stated that individual members of paramilitary groups are involved in ‘serious criminal activity’. Examples cited in the assessment include: ‘large scale smuggling operations, fuel laundering, drug dealing and extortion of local businesses’.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-10-28T15:18:00.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423487/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423487/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-10-23","Organised Crime: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the level of paramilitary-linked organised crime in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL2951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423488","Home Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>The Home Office has made no specific assessment of the level of crime against older people, and fear of crime amongst older people. The attached tablesshow figures from the independent Crime Survey for England and Wales (CSEW) for the year to March 2015 for (1) the percentage of adults in each age group who were victims of crime, and (2) the percentage of adults in each age group who had high levels of worry about crime.</p><p>Police reform is working and the Crime Survey shows that overall crime is down by more than a quarter since 2010. We continue to develop the role of our elected and accountable Police and Crime Commissioners to shape policing services to local needs and priorities, as they are now doing in commissioning victims’ services, setting policing priorities and driving reform.</p><br />",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-12T14:44:19.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423488/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423488/answer","Attached tables.docx","Figures from CSEW","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423488/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Crime: Older People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the level of (1) crime against older people, and (2) fear of crime amongst older people; and what steps they are taking to address both the incidence and fear of crime against older people.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL2952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423489","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Universal Credit programme publishes official experimental statistics which are available on GOV.UK.</p><br /><p>The statistics to 10 September show that 125,877 people were on the Universal Credit caseload. Cost information for the current UC caseload is not available for publication.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-10-30T11:46:38.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423489/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423489/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-23","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people currently receive Universal Credit, and at what cost to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423490","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>The Emergency Services Mobile Communications Programme has had on-going discussions and workshops with the emergency services, including those in Scotland, about all aspects of the new network including coverage requirements in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-04T16:52:43.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423490/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423490/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Emergency Services: Scotland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the emergency services in Scotland about ensuring that the new communications network being procured under the emergency services mobile communications programme meets the coverage requirements of rural and island communities.","false","Biography information for Lord Paddick",,"Lord Paddick","HL2954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423491","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>The Home Office meets senior managers from Airwave Solutions Ltd regularly to discuss the service that ASL provides. The Home Office’s plans for transition from the existing Airwave service to the future ESN service is regularly discussed at these meetings.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-04T16:52:21.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423491/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423491/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Emergency Services: Telecommunications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with Airwave Solutions about the transition of emergency services communications as part of the emergency services mobile communications programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Paddick",,"Lord Paddick","HL2955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423492","Home Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) is the international body that writes standards for 4G technology (http://www.3gpp.org/) . The Home Office has been attending a number of working groups within 3GPP since November 2012.</p><p>In January 2015 a new working group within 3GPP, SA6 Mission-critical applications was created specifically to standardise mission-critical voice functionality over 4G networks. The Home Office supported the creation of SA6, currently funds the chairman of that working group, and sends other attendees to this, as well as related meetings within 3GPP.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-09T15:27:49.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423492/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423492/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Emergency Services: Telecommunications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to push for a global standard for mission-critical voice functionality over commercial 4G networks.","false","Biography information for Lord Paddick",,"Lord Paddick","HL2956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423493","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-02","<p>This action was brought under section 5 of the Protection of Children Act 1978. The Government believes in freedom of expression in the arts, but it is imperative that we have robust laws to prevent the making of indecent images of children. Decisions on the destruction of any artwork are made by our independent courts and may be subject to appeal.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-11-02T16:42:52.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423493/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423493/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-23","Graham Ovenden","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government under what legislation the Metropolitan Police has brought the action against Graham Ovenden to order his collection of art to be forfeited and destroyed.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL2957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423494","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-04","<br /><p>The relocation of 150 Company from Redhill to Croydon was part of the redesign of the Army Reserve as part of Future Reserves 2020 and Army 2020. In this case the Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers were realigned to better integrate the Reserve component with their Regular Army partners. It also sought to maximise the potential for future recruitment, which in some cases necessitated the relocation of smaller units and sub-units.</p><p>While it was recognised that the infrastructure of the Croydon Army Reserve Centre required some improvement, it was deemed no worse than that at Redhill Army Reserve Centre. Therefore, an early move was agreed to realise the wider benefit of an increased recruiting footprint, thus ensuring that 103 Battalion REME could grow in strength and maintain the critical mass necessary for effective training and therefore operational capability</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-11-04T15:39:43.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423494/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423494/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-23","Army Reserve: Croydon","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 22 October (HL2256), why 150 Recovery Company, part of 103 Battalion Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers, relocated from the Army Reserve Centre at Redhill to the one at Croydon, in the light of the fact that the related infrastructure developments had not progressed past the initial assessment phase.","false","Biography information for Earl Attlee",,"Earl Attlee","HL2958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423495","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>The consultation we have recently published on tackling labour exploitation sets out the role envisaged for the Director of Labour Market Enforcement. The measures we have introduced in the Immigration Bill require the Director to set the priorities for the three enforcement bodies: the Employment Agency Standards Inspectorate, National Minimum Wage enforcement function of HMRC and the Gangmasters Licensing Authority. These will be set out in an annual strategic plan, subject to the approval of the Secretaries of State at the Department for Business Innovation and Skills and the Home Office. This will set out the clear priorities for tackling serious exploitation and the role of the agencies in delivering them.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-04T17:01:33.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423495/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423495/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role in the Director of Labour Market Enforcement, as set out in the Immigration Bill, will play in setting the operational priorities of and in allocating resources to (1) the Employment Agency Standards Inspectorate, (2) the Gangmasters Licensing Authority, and (3) HM Revenue and Customs National Minimum Wage enforcement teams.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL2959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423496","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>Following a commitment made in section 55 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 the Government has now launched a consultation on tackling exploitation in the labour market. This consultation is seeking views on proposals to appoint a new Director of Labour Market Enforcement and create additional powers for the Gangmasters Licensing Authority to take enforcement action against labour exploitation across the labour market. The consultation proposes a power to vary the sectors subject to licensing following an evidence-based analysis by the new Director.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-04T17:02:12.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423496/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423496/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to introduce labour-market wide licensing and enforcement in order to support commitments made in the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL2960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423497","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>Section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 focuses on encouraging businesses to take action to prevent modern slavery in their supply chains. The state seeks to prevent this type of abuse through labour inspection and enforcement. We want these two areas of activity to complement each other to prevent labour exploitation in the UK. We have recently launched a consultation on the Government’s approach to tackling exploitation in the labour market. We will use the outcomes of this consultation to ensure that our final proposals complement section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act as effectively as possible.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-04T17:03:30.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423497/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423497/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with business on how labour inspection and enforcement could support implementation of section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015, relating to transparency in the supply chains of commercial organisations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL2961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423498","Home Office","false","2015-11-06","<p>We are currently consulting on the future role and remit of the Gangmasters Licensing Authority, including the licensing regime and its operation. Any changes made to the GLA’s licensing regime would be undertaken in line with the principles of Managing Public Money and would be subject to Her Majesty's Treasury and Home Office Ministers’ approval.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-06T13:28:54.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423498/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423498/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Gangmasters: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to increasing the Gangmasters Licensing Authority fees for licence applications, renewal and inspection for the top two bands of businesses, in order to raise income to cover that Authority's expenditure.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL2962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423499","Home Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority does not provide data breakdown of compensation awarded to victims by crime type. This is because it awards compensation in line with the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme tariff of injuries rather than by the type of incident that led to those injuries.</p><p>Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service (HMCTS) administers civil claims, employment tribunal claims, and court-awarded criminal compensation. Civil claims and employment tribunal claims do not deal with cases where a crime has been alleged, so data is not recorded on victims of modern slavery. For court-awarded criminal compensations, the sentence passed on offenders for each offence committed is recorded, including any compensation awarded. This data is not cross-referenced against compensation received by victims of the offence, so compensation received by victims of trafficking for labour exploitation is not recorded.</p><p>There are no plans to change the way data is collected by CICA or HMCTS that would provide the information sought about compensation received by victims of trafficking for labour exploitation.</p><p>HMRC work with the police, Home Office and local authorities in cases that may involve slavery and servitude. HMRC do not collate specific data on arrears identified but are currently reviewing ways to record any National Minimum Wage outcomes in Modern Slavery cases they undertake.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-09T16:57:14.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423499/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423499/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Human Trafficking: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to keep records on the amount of compensation received by victims of trafficking for labour exploitation through (1) the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority, (2) civil claims for damages, (3) employment tribunal claims, (4) court-awarded criminal compensation, and (5) repayments for breaches of the National Minimum Wage.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL2963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423500","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>Article 39 of the Asylum Procedures Directive requires that EU member states must provide an effective remedy before a Court or Tribunal in respect of a decision taken on a person’s asylum application.</p><p>The nature of the remedy is not prescribed beyond requiring it to be before a Court or Tribunal.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-02T14:44:30.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423500/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423500/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-23","Asylum: Appeals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 19 October (HL2532), which specific elements of European law require the right to challenge an adverse asylum decision via an effective remedy; and whether the nature of such a remedy is prescribed.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL2964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423501","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-06","<p>The table below lists each public inquiry launched by the Government to investigate the death of a single individual since 1988. It shows the purpose of the inquiry and the timing of the inquiry from its launch to publication of the inquiry report.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Individual </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Purpose</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Duration</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Stephen Lawrence</strong></p></td><td><p>To inquire into the matters arising from his death on 22 April 1993, in order particularly to identify the lessons to be learned for the investigation and prosecution of racially motivated crimes.</p></td><td><p>July 1997 – February 1999</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Victoria Climbié</strong></p></td><td><p>To establish the circumstances leading to and surrounding her death.</p></td><td><p>May 2001 – January 2003</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Dr David Kelly</strong></p></td><td><p>To conduct an investigation into the circumstances surrounding his death.</p></td><td><p>July 2003 – January 2004</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Zahid Mubarek</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate his death and the events leading up to the attack on him, and make recommendations about the prevention of such attacks in the future.</p></td><td><p>April 2004 – June 2006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Robert Hamill</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate whether any wrongful act or omission by or within the Royal Ulster Constabulary facilitated his death or obstructed the investigation of it, or whether attempts were made to do so; whether any such act or omission was intentional or negligent; and whether the investigation of his death was carried out with due diligence. (This followed a recommendation of the Cory Collusion Inquiry.)</p></td><td><p>November 2004 – February 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Billy Wright</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate whether any wrongful act or omission by or within the prison authorities or other state agencies facilitated his death, or whether attempts were made to do so; and whether any such act or omission was intentional or negligent. (This followed a recommendation of the Cory Collusion Inquiry.)</p></td><td><p>November 2004 – October 2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Rosemary Nelson</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate whether any wrongful act or omission by or within the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland Office, Army or other state agency facilitated her death or obstructed the investigation of it, or whether attempts were made to do so; whether any such act or omission was intentional or negligent; and whether the investigation of her death was carried out with due diligence. (This followed a recommendation of the Cory Collusion Inquiry.)</p></td><td><p>November 2004 – May 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Baha Mousa</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate the circumstances surrounding the death of Baha Mousa, an Iraqi civilian who died in Iraq in 2003 and the treatment of others detained with him by the British armed forces.</p></td><td><p>August 2008 – September 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Bernard (Sonny) Lodge</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate his death at HMP Manchester in August 1998. (An ad hoc investigation began in September 2008 and was converted into a 2005 Act inquiry.)</p></td><td><p>February 2009 – December 2009</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Azelle Rodney</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate the death of Azelle Rodney who was shot by a police marksman in North London on 30 April 2005.</p></td><td><p>June 2010 – July 2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Alexander Litvinenko</strong></p></td><td><p>To investigate his death on 23 November 2006. (The inquest was converted into a 2005 Act inquiry following a judicial review.)</p></td><td><p>July 2014 – present</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /> <br />",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-11-06T12:35:22.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423501/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423501/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-23","Public Inquiries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what public inquiries they have instigated into the death of a single individual since 1988; who were those individuals; why they were referred for a public inquiry in each case; and on which dates they were referred.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423502","Attorney General","false","2015-11-06","<p>Non-consolidated performance related awards are only paid to reward excellence, for example to recognise and incentivise those responsible for delivering high quality public services and savings to the taxpayer. Those one-off payments are not pensionable. Furthermore, since 2010/11 the Government has restricted awards for senior civil servants to the top 25% of performers (from 65% in previous years), saving around £15 million overall.</p><br /><p>A table showing information on performance related awards made by the Law Officers’ Departments during the past three financial years is presented below.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="7"><p><strong>Law Officer’s Departments – Performance awards</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong></strong> <strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong></strong> <strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong></strong> <strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong></strong> <strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Year end</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>In year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Year end</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>In year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Year end</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>In year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Government Legal Department **</strong></p></td><td><p>£531,105</p></td><td><p>£144,013</p></td><td><p>£755,080</p></td><td><p>£139,635</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>£182,376</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Crown Prosecution Service ***</strong></p></td><td><p>£128,347</p></td><td><p>None</p></td><td><p>£98,261</p></td><td><p>None</p></td><td><p>£115,453</p></td><td><p>None</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Serious Fraud Office</strong></p></td><td><p>£235,872</p></td><td><p>£34,293</p></td><td><p>£236,051</p></td><td><p>£75,946</p></td><td><p>£232,080</p></td><td><p>£92,505</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* The year-end figures for the 2014/15 performance year are not yet finalised.</p><p>** The increase in the sums for GLD reflects the fact that the department has significantly increased in size each year since 2011, as a result of consolidation of government legal teams into a single department. The GLD data also covers the Attorney General’s Office and HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate.</p><p>*** The only bonus scheme operated within the CPS is for SCS grades or the equivalent Senior Legal Manager (SLM) grades.</p><br /><p>Further details on staff numbers and costs, including performance related pay are published in the respective departmental Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2015-11-06T13:37:17.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423502/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423502/answer",,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-10-23","Law Officers' Departments: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much was paid in (a) year end and (b) in-year bonuses to officials in the Law Officers' Departments in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","13168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423503","Attorney General","false","2015-10-28","<p>Information relating to internal discussion and advice is not normally disclosed.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2015-10-28T14:39:43.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423503/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423503/answer",,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-10-23","Ministers: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what discussions he has had with his ministerial colleagues in the Cabinet Office on the removal from the Ministerial Code of a reference to Ministers having a duty to comply with the law including international law and treaty obligations and to uphold the administration of justice.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","13253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423504","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p>a) The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) currently funds a programme through the Tinder Foundation with the aim of equipping up to 1m adults with the basic digital skills, motivation and confidence to go online, be digitally capable and to be safe online. The contract was awarded by open competitive tender in October 2014 and has a maximum value of £15m. This addresses Action 2 of the Digital Inclusion Strategy 2014 (to establish a quality cross-government digital capability programme).</p><br /><p>In addition the adult skills budget managed by the Skills Funding Agency continues to support learners to increase skills, competence and knowledge including basic digital skills and capabilities as called for under Action 1 of the Strategy.</p><br /><p>b) There are no other projects currently planned.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-29T14:44:31.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423504/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423504/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-23","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what (a) funding his Department is undertaking and (b) projects his Department has planned as part of the Government's Digital Inclusion Strategy.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","13243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423505","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-02","<p>Non-consolidated performance related pay is paid to reward excellence, for example to recognise and incentivise those responsible for delivering high quality public services and savings to the taxpayer. These one-off payments are not pensionable. Since 2010-11 the Government has restricted awards for senior civil servants to the top 25% of performers (from 65% in previous years), saving around £15 million overall.</p><p>An element of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills overall pay award for staff below the Senior Civil Service (SCS) is allocated to non-consolidated, non-pensionable pay related to performance. There are two types of award: in-year awards and annual performance awards.</p><p>Performance awards for the SCS are part of the pay system across the whole Senior Civil Service, and are used to reward high performance sustained throughout the year.</p><p>Information in the table shows the cost of each of these type of awards in each of the last three years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Non-SCS End year Annual Performance Awards</p></td><td><p>Non-SCS In-Year Awards</p></td><td><p>SCS Annual Performance Awards</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£1,540,773</p></td><td><p>£332,080</p></td><td><p>£577,925</p></td><td><p>£2,450,778</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£990,360</p></td><td><p>£492,228</p></td><td><p>£576,000</p></td><td><p>£2,058,588</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£1,288,474*</p></td><td><p>£605,608</p></td><td><p>£539,500</p></td><td><p>£2,433,582</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* A few end year payments still to be made so this figure is the latest and may increase</p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-11-02T15:10:46.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423505/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423505/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-23","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much was paid in (a) year end and (b) in-year bonuses to officials of his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","13158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423506","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>Following a request from the Open Data User Group (ODUG) to the Data Strategy Board in 2013, the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills funded an independent advisory report into the feasibility and options for the creation of an open address data set. The report was published in February 2014 and is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/274979/bis-14-513-open-national-address-gazetteer.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/274979/bis-14-513-open-national-address-gazetteer.pdf</a><br></p><p>The estimated cost of an open data product – £40m per annum to Government – was considered unaffordable by the Public Sector Transparency Board (which subsumed the DSB).</p><br /><p>However following extensive consultation and engagement with the market since the commissioning of the report in 2013 Royal Mail has simplified it’s Postcode Address File (PAF) licence. They have also introduced new measures to provide free access to PAF for micro businesses and small independent charities.</p><br /><p>In addition, from 1 April 2014, eligible public sector organisations in England and Wales, and Scotland, have been able to take advantage of the new Public Sector Licence, which reduces the overall cost for those organisations and simplifies access to address data.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-29T14:48:10.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423506/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423506/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-23","Post Codes: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the potential economic value of the UK having an address file that was published as open data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","13140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423507","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-28","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister stated during a speech made in Singapore on 28 July that he has asked Land Registry from this autumn to publish data on which foreign companies own which land and property titles in England and Wales. <br></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-28T17:32:22.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423507/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423507/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-23","Foreign Companies: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he expects the Land Registry to publish data on which foreign companies own which land property titles in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","13201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423508","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-28","<p>I refer my hon. Member to the answer given on the 26 October 2015 to Question UIN 12727.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-28T15:01:42.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423508/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423508/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-23","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the practice of insurers automatically signing up customers to annual renewals without the explicit consent of those policy holders.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","13204"
